Tests on mean values

Introduction

Hypothesis tests and p-values

  • Motivation

    • Population mean and sample mean
    • Understand the question
    • Explore the data

  • Comparing one-sample mean to a known mean:

    • One-sample t-test (parametric)
    • One-sample Wilcoxon test (non-parametric)

  • Comparing the means of two independent groups

    • Unpaired two samples t-test (parametric)
    • Unpaired two-samples Wilcoxon test (non-parametric)

  • Comparing the means of paired samples

    • Paired samples t-test (parametric)
    • Paired samples Wilcoxon test (non-parametric)

  • Comparing the means of more than two groups

    • One-way ANOVA test (parametric)
    • Kruskal-Wallis test (non parametric)

Data example 1

Studies of pulmonary function in adults who are long-time smokers have shown that smoking tends to impair lung function. A question then arises as to whether similar effects can be detected in children who smoke. We will use fev data that include measures of lung function, forced expiratory volume (FEV), which were collected from 654 children seen for a routine checkup in a pediatric clinic. The study subjects were asked whether they were current smokers. FEV measures the volume of air you can blow out of your lungs.

library(Hmisc)
#fev=read.csv("./data/fev.csv",header=TRUE,row.names=1)
fev <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/couthcommander/sip_computing/main/labs/fev.csv",header=TRUE,row.names=1)
label(fev$age) <- 'subject age at time of measurement (years)'
label(fev$fev) <- 'measured FEV (liters per second)'
label(fev$height) <- 'subject height at time of measurement (inches)'
label(fev$sex) <- 'sex (1 = male, 2 = female)'
label(fev$smoke) <- 'smoker (1 = smoker, 2 = non-smoker)'

Comparing one-sample mean to a known mean

Question: Is the mean value of age in this data different from 10?

Check data distribution to decide which test to use

hist(fev$age, main="", xlab="Age")
abline(v=10, lty=2, col="red")

One-sample t-test (parametric)

#T stastic caculation
cohortMean=mean(fev$age)
cohortSD=sd(fev$age)
cohortN=nrow(fev)
populationMean=10

TValue=(cohortMean-populationMean)/(cohortSD/sqrt(cohortN))
TValue
## [1] -0.5956932
#one sample t test
t.test(fev$age, mu=populationMean)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  fev$age
## t = -0.59569, df = 653, p-value = 0.5516
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 10
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   9.704381 10.158005
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  9.931193

The output of t.test() function is a list containing the following components:

  • statistic: the value of the t-statistic

  • p.value: the p-value for the test

  • conf.int: a confidence interval for the mean appropriate to the specified alternative hypothesis.

  • estimate: the estimated mean for one-sample test or difference in means for the two groups being compared (in the case of two-sample t-test).

One-sample Wilcoxon test (non-parametric)

wilcox.test(fev$age, mu = populationMean)
## 
##  Wilcoxon signed rank test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  fev$age
## V = 76710, p-value = 0.1613
## alternative hypothesis: true location is not equal to 10

hist(fev$fev[which(fev$smoke==2)], main="Non-smokers", xlab="FEV")

boxplot(fev$fev~fev$smoke, main="", ylab="FEV", xlab="Smoking behaviors")

tapply(fev$fev, fev$smoke,summary)

Two-sample t-test (parametric)

T-statistic calculation

#T statistic calculation
dataX=(fev$fev[which(fev$smoke==1)])
dataY=(fev$fev[which(fev$smoke==2)])

meanX=mean(dataX)
meanY=mean(dataY)
sdX=sd(dataX)
sdY=sd(dataY)
nX=length(dataX)
nY=length(dataY)

TValue=(meanX-meanY)/(sqrt(sdX^2/nX+sdY^2/nY))
TValue
## [1] 7.149608

Two-sample t-test

t.test(dataX, dataY, alternative = "two.sided", paired = FALSE)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  dataX and dataY
## t = 7.1496, df = 83.273, p-value = 3.074e-10
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.5130126 0.9084253
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  3.276862  2.566143

Wilcoxon rank sum test (non-parametric):

Wilcoxon rank sum test is a non-parametric test for means of independent two samples.

wilcox.test(dataX,dataY)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  dataX and dataY
## W = 28686, p-value = 4.071e-11
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

Comparing the mean of paired samples

Lets compare Immunoglobulin G (IgG) to SARS-CoV-2 spike receptor-binding domain (RBD) values between the baseline (rbd1) and three weeks following first vaccine dose (rbd2).

Paired t-test (parametric)

Data summary for changes in RBD between the baseline and three weeks following first vaccine dose

summary(dataForAnalysis$rbd2-dataForAnalysis$rbd1)
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
## -0.19400 -0.01425  0.07300  0.36355  0.62875  1.92100
hist(dataForAnalysis$rbd2-dataForAnalysis$rbd1, main="", xlab="Changes in RBD between the baseline and 3-weeks follow-up")

plot(dataForAnalysis$rbd1, dataForAnalysis$rbd2, main="", xlab="RBD at baseline", ylab="RBD at follow-up")
abline(0, 1, lty=2, col="red")

T-statistic calculation on difference

#T stastic caculation
diffValue=dataForAnalysis$rbd1-dataForAnalysis$rbd2

cohortMean=mean(diffValue)
cohortSD=sd(diffValue)
cohortN=length(diffValue)
populationMean=0

TValue=(cohortMean-populationMean)/(cohortSD/sqrt(cohortN))
TValue
## [1] -6.100996

Paired t-test

t.test(dataForAnalysis$rbd1, dataForAnalysis$rbd2, paired = TRUE)
## 
##  Paired t-test
## 
## data:  dataForAnalysis$rbd1 and dataForAnalysis$rbd2
## t = -6.101, df = 79, p-value = 3.678e-08
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.4821582 -0.2449418
## sample estimates:
## mean of the differences 
##                -0.36355

You will get same results by one sample t-test to compare the difference with mean=0

t.test(dataForAnalysis$rbd1-dataForAnalysis$rbd2, mu=0)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  dataForAnalysis$rbd1 - dataForAnalysis$rbd2
## t = -6.101, df = 79, p-value = 3.678e-08
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.4821582 -0.2449418
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  -0.36355

Wilcoxon signed rank test (non-parametric)

Wilcoxon signed rank test is a non-parametric test for the mean of paired two samples.

wilcox.test(dataForAnalysis$rbd1, dataForAnalysis$rbd2, paired = TRUE)
## 
##  Wilcoxon signed rank test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  dataForAnalysis$rbd1 and dataForAnalysis$rbd2
## V = 556, p-value = 3.381e-07
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

Analysis of Variance (ANOVA): testing means for three or more samples

The ANOVA test assumes that the data are normally distributed and the variance across groups are homogeneous.

Lets compare the baseline RBD values (rbd1) between different groups of organ transplant patients, as well as three weeks following first vaccine dose (rbd2).

organ: Transplant organ type (0 = healthy control, 1 = kidney, 2 = liver, 3 = heart, 4 = lung).

Data visualization

boxplot(rbd1 ~ organ, data = dataForAnalysis, main="", xlab="Transplant organ type", ylab="RBD at the baseline")

boxplot(rbd2 ~ organ, data = dataForAnalysis, main="", xlab="Transplant organ type", ylab="RBD at the 3-weeks follow-up")

hist(dataForAnalysis$rbd1, main="", xlab="RBD at the baseline")

hist(dataForAnalysis$rbd2, main="", xlab="RBD at the 3-weeks follow-up")

One-way ANOVA

dataForAnalysis$organ= factor(dataForAnalysis$organ)

#difference of baseline rbd between organ types
anovaResult1 <- aov(rbd1 ~ organ, data = dataForAnalysis)
summary(anovaResult1)

Kruskal-Wallis test

Kruskal-Wallis test is a non-parametric alternative to one-way ANOVA test, which extends Wilcoxon rank sum test when there are more than two groups.

#baselilne rbd
kruskal.test(rbd1 ~ organ, data = dataForAnalysis)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  rbd1 by organ
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 3.0456, df = 4, p-value = 0.5502
#rbd at three weeks following first vaccine dose
kruskal.test(rbd2 ~ organ, data = dataForAnalysis)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  rbd2 by organ
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 39.836, df = 4, p-value = 4.68e-08
pairwise.wilcox.test(dataForAnalysis$rbd2 , dataForAnalysis$organ,
                 p.adjust.method = "BH")
## 
##  Pairwise comparisons using Wilcoxon rank sum exact test 
## 
## data:  dataForAnalysis$rbd2 and dataForAnalysis$organ 
## 
##   0       1      2      3     
## 1 1.3e-07 -      -      -     
## 2 4.9e-05 0.3181 -      -     
## 3 1.1e-05 0.3181 0.0946 -     
## 4 0.0013  0.4539 0.3181 1.0000
## 
## P value adjustment method: BH
